{"title_page": "Anne Simpson", "text_new": "{{For|those of a similar name|Ann Simpson (disambiguation)}}\n\n'''Anne Simpson''' is a Canadian poet, novelist, artist and essayist. She was a recipient of the [[Griffin Poetry Prize]].\n\n==Biography==\nSimpson received her [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] and [[Master of Arts|M.A.]] degrees from [[Queen's University at Kingston|Queen's University]], and graduated in Fine Arts from [[OCAD University]] (formerly the Ontario College of Art).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.writers.ns.ca/writers/S/simpsonanne.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-07-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928092758/http://www.writers.ns.ca/writers/S/simpsonanne.html |archivedate=2011-09-28 }}</ref> Subsequently, she worked as a [[CUSO]] volunteer English teacher for two years in [[Nigeria]]. She is an adjunct professor at [[St. Francis Xavier University]], where she established the Writing Centre.\n\nSimpson was the co-winner of the 1997 [[Journey Prize]], awarded for her short story ''Dreaming Snow''.  Her second collection of poetry, ''Loop'' (McClelland & Stewart, 2003), was the winner of the 2004 Canadian [[Griffin Poetry Prize]]. ''Loop'' contains many poems composed in sequences, including, notably, a poetic demonstration of a M\u00f6bius strip.<ref>Judges Citation , Griffin Trust Poetry Prize 2004</ref>\n\nHer other poetry collections include ''Light Falls Through You'' (McClelland & Stewart, 2000), winner of the [[Gerald Lampert Award]] and the [[Atlantic Poetry Prize]],  ''Quick'' (McClelland & Stewart, 2007), winner of the Pat Lowther Award, and ''Is'' (McClelland & Stewart, 2011) in which Simpson 'negotiates an ever-changing path between language and structure'.<ref>Review of 'Is'- Vancouver Sun, 2011</ref>\n\nSimpson has written two novels: ''Canterbury Beach'' (Penguin, 2001) and ''Falling'' (McClelland & Stewart, 2008), which was a Canadian bestseller and winner of the Dartmouth Fiction Award. It was long-listed for the [[International Dublin Literary Award]].\n\nShe has also written a book of essays on poetics, ''The Marram Grass: Poetry and Otherness'' (Gaspereau, 2009).\n\nSimpson has been the writer-in-residence at a number of institutions, including the [[University of New Brunswick]], the Medical Humanities Program at [[Dalhousie University]], the [[Saskatoon Public Library]], the [[University of Prince Edward Island]], Dalhousie University, and [[Memorial University of Newfoundland|Memorial University]].<ref>http://today.mun.ca/news.php?news_id=6569</ref> She has been a faculty member at Sage Hill Writing Experience and the Banff Centre.\n\n== Bibliography ==\n;Poetry\n*''Light Falls Through You'' \u2013 [[2000 in poetry|2000]] (winner of the [[Gerald Lampert Award]] and the [[Atlantic Poetry Prize]]) {{ISBN|0-7710-8077-8}}\n*''Loop'' \u2013 [[2003 in poetry|2003]] (shortlisted for the 2003 [[Governor General's Award]], winner of the 2004 Canadian [[Griffin Poetry Prize]]) {{ISBN|0-7710-8075-1}}\n*''Quick'' \u2013 2007 {{ISBN|0-7710-8091-3}} (winner of the 2008 [[Pat Lowther Award]])<ref name = award>{{cite web |url= http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/books/story/2008/06/23/poetry-awards.html |title=Press Release: N.S., Toronto poets win League of Canadian Poets honours \u2013 Arts & Entertainment \u2013 CBC News  |work=cbc.ca |date=June 23, 2008 |accessdate=24 April 2012}}</ref>\n*''Is'' \u2013 2011 {{ISBN|978-0-7710-8051-7}}\n\n;Novels\n*''Canterbury Beach'' \u2013 2001 (shortlisted for the [[Thomas Head Raddall Award]]) {{ISBN|0-670-89484-2}}\n*''Falling'' \u2013 2008  {{ISBN|978-0-7710-8090-6}}\n\n;Essays\n*''[https://web.archive.org/web/20101031180702/http://www.gaspereau.com/1554470307.shtml A Ragged Pen: Essays on Poetry & Memory]'' \u2013 2006 Gaspereau Press {{ISBN|978-1-55447-030-3}}\n*''[https://web.archive.org/web/20090211063240/http://gaspereau.com/1554470714.shtml The Marram Grass: Poetry & Otherness]'' \u2013 2009 Gaspereau Press  {{ISBN|978-1-55447-071-6}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*[http://www.griffinpoetryprize.com/awards-and-poets/shortlists/2004-shortlist/anne-simpson/ Griffin Poetry Prize biography, poetry reading extract and citation]\n*[http://www.artsandopinion.com/2003_v2_n4/simpson.htm Seven small poems 2003\u2013 Arts & Opinion Vol 2 no 4 ]\n*[http://www.griffinpoetryprize.com/london-2004 Example of Simpson's poetry- 'Orpheus afterwards']\n*[http://www.annesimpson.ca/art/ Examples of Simpson's Art]\n*[http://www.annesimpson.ca/ Simpson writing website]\n*[http://writers.ns.ca/members/profile/187 Writer's Federation of Nova Scotia Biography]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Simpson, Anne}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian poets]]\n[[Category:Queen's University alumni]]\n[[Category:Canadian women novelists]]\n[[Category:Canadian women poets]]\n[[Category:Canadian women essayists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian women writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian essayists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian essayists]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|those of a similar name|Ann Simpson (disambiguation)}}\n\n'''Anne Simpson''' is a Canadian poet, novelist, artist and essayist. She was a recipient of the [[Griffin Poetry Prize]].\n\n==Biography==\nSimpson received her [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] and [[Master of Arts|M.A.]] degrees from [[Queen's University at Kingston|Queen's University]], and graduated in Fine Arts from [[OCAD  University]] (formerly the Ontario College of Art).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.writers.ns.ca/writers/S/simpsonanne.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-07-18 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110928092758/http://www.writers.ns.ca/writers/S/simpsonanne.html |archivedate=2011-09-28 }}</ref> Subsequently, she worked as a [[CUSO]] volunteer English teacher for two years in [[Nigeria]]. She is an adjunct professor at [[St. Francis Xavier University]], where she established the Writing Centre.\n\nSimpson was the co-winner of the 1997 [[Journey Prize]], awarded for her short story ''Dreaming Snow''.  Her second collection of poetry, ''Loop'' (McClelland & Stewart, 2003), was the winner of the 2004 Canadian [[Griffin Poetry Prize]]. ''Loop'' contains many poems composed in sequences, including, notably, a poetic demonstration of a M\u00f6bius strip.<ref>Judges Citation , Griffin Trust Poetry Prize 2004</ref>\n\nHer other poetry collections include ''Light Falls Through You'' (McClelland & Stewart, 2000), winner of the [[Gerald Lampert Award]] and the [[Atlantic Poetry Prize]],  ''Quick'' (McClelland & Stewart, 2007), winner of the Pat Lowther Award, and ''Is'' (McClelland & Stewart, 2011) in which Simpson 'negotiates an ever-changing path between language and structure'.<ref>Review of 'Is'- Vancouver Sun, 2011</ref>\n\nSimpson has written two novels: ''Canterbury Beach'' (Penguin, 2001) and ''Falling'' (McClelland & Stewart, 2008), which was a Canadian bestseller and winner of the Dartmouth Fiction Award. It was long-listed for the [[International Dublin Literary Award]].\n\nShe has also written a book of essays on poetics, ''The Marram Grass: Poetry and Otherness'' (Gaspereau, 2009).\n\nSimpson has been the writer-in-residence at a number of institutions, including the [[University of New Brunswick]], the Medical Humanities Program at [[Dalhousie University]], the [[Saskatoon Public Library]], the [[University of Prince Edward Island]], Dalhousie University, and [[Memorial University of Newfoundland|Memorial University]].<ref>http://today.mun.ca/news.php?news_id=6569</ref> She has been a faculty member at Sage Hill Writing Experience and the Banff Centre.\n\n== Bibliography ==\n;Poetry\n*''Light Falls Through You'' \u2013 [[2000 in poetry|2000]] (winner of the [[Gerald Lampert Award]] and the [[Atlantic Poetry Prize]]) {{ISBN|0-7710-8077-8}}\n*''Loop'' \u2013 [[2003 in poetry|2003]] (shortlisted for the 2003 [[Governor General's Award]], winner of the 2004 Canadian [[Griffin Poetry Prize]]) {{ISBN|0-7710-8075-1}}\n*''Quick'' \u2013 2007 {{ISBN|0-7710-8091-3}} (winner of the 2008 [[Pat Lowther Award]])<ref name = award>{{cite web |url= http://www.cbc.ca/news/arts/books/story/2008/06/23/poetry-awards.html |title=Press Release: N.S., Toronto poets win League of Canadian Poets honours \u2013 Arts & Entertainment \u2013 CBC News  |work=cbc.ca |date=June 23, 2008 |accessdate=24 April 2012}}</ref>\n*''Is'' \u2013 2011 {{ISBN|978-0-7710-8051-7}}\n\n;Novels\n*''Canterbury Beach'' \u2013 2001 (shortlisted for the [[Thomas Head Raddall Award]]) {{ISBN|0-670-89484-2}}\n*''Falling'' \u2013 2008  {{ISBN|978-0-7710-8090-6}}\n\n;Essays\n*''[https://web.archive.org/web/20101031180702/http://www.gaspereau.com/1554470307.shtml A Ragged Pen: Essays on Poetry & Memory]'' \u2013 2006 Gaspereau Press {{ISBN|978-1-55447-030-3}}\n*''[https://web.archive.org/web/20090211063240/http://gaspereau.com/1554470714.shtml The Marram Grass: Poetry & Otherness]'' \u2013 2009 Gaspereau Press  {{ISBN|978-1-55447-071-6}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*[http://www.griffinpoetryprize.com/awards-and-poets/shortlists/2004-shortlist/anne-simpson/ Griffin Poetry Prize biography, poetry reading extract and citation]\n*[http://www.artsandopinion.com/2003_v2_n4/simpson.htm Seven small poems 2003\u2013 Arts & Opinion Vol 2 no 4 ]\n*[http://www.griffinpoetryprize.com/london-2004 Example of Simpson's poetry- 'Orpheus afterwards']\n*[http://www.annesimpson.ca/art/ Examples of Simpson's Art]\n*[http://www.annesimpson.ca/ Simpson writing website]\n*[http://writers.ns.ca/members/profile/187 Writer's Federation of Nova Scotia Biography]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Simpson, Anne}}\n[[Category:1956 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian poets]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian novelists]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian poets]]\n[[Category:Queen's University alumni]]\n[[Category:Canadian essayists]]\n[[Category:Canadian women novelists]]\n[[Category:Canadian women poets]]\n[[Category:Canadian women essayists]]\n[[Category:20th-century Canadian women writers]]\n[[Category:21st-century Canadian women writers]]\n[[Category:20th-century essayists]]\n[[Category:21st-century essayists]]\n", "name_user": "Bearcat", "label": "safe", "comment": "recat", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Anne_Simpson"}
{"title_page": "Jung Yong-hwa", "text_new": "{{short description|South Korean singer and actor}}\n{{Redirect|Yong-hwa|the mountain|Yonghwasan|the name (and other people with the same name)|Yong-hwa (name)}}\n{{Korean name|Jung}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=September 2014}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name                = Jung Yong-hwa\n| image               = Jung Yong-hwa - Cook Up a Storm meet and greet 5.jpg\n| caption             = Jung promoting ''[[Cook Up a Storm]]'' in Macau, 2017\n| birth_name         =  Jung Yong-hwa\n| birth_date          = {{birth date and age|1989|06|22}}\n| birth_place         = [[Yeoksam-dong]], [[Gangnam-gu]], [[Seoul]], South Korea \n| origin              = \n| occupation          = {{hlist|Musician|singer|songwriter|rapper|composer|record producer|actor}}\n| module             = {{Infobox musical artist|embed=yes      \n| background         = solo_singer\n| genre               = {{hlist|[[Rock music|Rock]]|[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]|[[Pop music|pop]]|[[Jazz music|jazz]]|[[Hip hop music|hop hop]]}}\n| instrument          = {{hlist|vocals|guitar}}\n| years_active        = 2009\u2013present\n| label               = [[FNC Entertainment|FNC]]\n|associated_acts    = [[CNBLUE]]\n| url         = {{URL|fncent.com/jungyonghwa}}\n}}}}\n{{Infobox Korean name\n| title  = [[Korean name]]\n| hangul = {{linktext|\uc815|\uc6a9\ud654}}\n| hanja  = {{linktext|\u912d|\u5bb9|\u548c}}\n| rr     = Jeong Yong-hwa\n| mr     = Ch\u014fng Yonghwa\n}}\n\n'''Jung Yong-hwa''' ({{ko-hhrm|\uc815\uc6a9\ud654}}; {{IPA-ko|t\u0255\u0259\u02d0\u014b jo\u014b hwa|pron}}; born June 22, 1989) is a South Korean musician, singer-songwriter, rapper, record producer and actor. He is the leader, lead vocalist and rhythm guitarist of the rock band [[CNBLUE]]. Jung made his television debut in ''[[You're Beautiful (TV series)|You're Beautiful]]'' (2009), and has since starred in television dramas ''[[Heartstrings (Korean TV series)|Heartstrings]]'' (2011), ''[[Marry Him If You Dare]]'' (2013), ''[[The Three Musketeers (2014 TV series)|The Three Musketeers]]'' (2014) and ''[[The Package (TV series)|The Package]]'' (2017). On the music front, Jung also made his solo debut with the album ''[[One Fine Day (Jung Yong-hwa album)|One Fine Day]]'' in 2015.\n\n==Early life and career beginnings==\nJung Yong-hwa was born on June 22, 1989, in [[Seoul]], South Korea.<ref name=\"Russell2014\">{{cite book|author=Mark Russell|title=K-Pop Now!: The Korean Music Revolution|page=56|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=etDZAwAAQBAJ|date=29 April 2014|publisher=Tuttle Publishing|isbn=978-1-4629-1411-1}}</ref> His family consists of his parents and a brother, who is four years older. He moved to [[Busan]] in 1991 and lived there through high school, where he first began composing music.<ref name=\"My name is\">{{cite web |language=ko |url=http://10.asiae.co.kr/Articles/new_view.htm?tsc=S1N54&a_id=2009113023070851564&pg= |title=\uc815\uc6a9\ud654\u2502My name is... |work=10Asia |accessdate=2011-03-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110813083200/http://10.asiae.co.kr/Articles/new_view.htm?tsc=S1N54&a_id=2009113023070851564&pg= |archive-date=August 13, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> After taking his college entrance, he moved back to Seoul, where he joined FNC Music. In 2009, Jung left for Japan to study music with his bandmates.<ref name=\"japanstay\" /> While there, they did street performances and released independent albums.<ref name=\"japanstay\">{{cite web|url=http://www.dcnews.in/news_list.php?code%3Dentertainment%26id%3D491963%26curPage%3D%26s_title%3D%26s_body%3D%26s_name%3D%26s_que%3D%26page%3D1 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2011-12-27 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120508232615/http://www.dcnews.in/news_list.php?code=entertainment&id=491963&curPage=&s_title=&s_body=&s_name=&s_que=&page=1 |archivedate=8 May 2012 }}</ref> The group debuted in Japan with the EP ''Now or Never'' on August 19, 2009 with an indie label [[AI Entertainment]]. They debuted in Korea in 2010 with the EP ''[[Bluetory]]'', and its lead single \"[[I'm a Loner]]\" became an instant hit in Korea.{{cn|date=January 2019}}\n\n==Music career==\nOn January 14, 2011, Jung released his first solo digital single, \"[[For First Time Lovers]]\". The song was featured on the [[We Got Married (Season 2)|second season of ''We Got Married'']], where Jung was a cast member and one half of an on-screen couple with [[Seohyun]] of [[Girls' Generation]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.tenasia.com/archives/5731|title=CNBLUE\u2019s Jung Yong-hwa releases song for first time couples|date=13 January 2011|work=10Asia}}</ref> Upon its release, it topped various South Korean music charts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.tenasia.com/archives/5754|title=CNBLUE Jung Yong-hwa\u2019s song sweeps online real-time music charts|date=14 January 2011|work=10Asia}}</ref> \n\nIn 2014, he released \"[[You, My Star]]\", a self-composed single dedicated to his fans. All profits of the single were donated to charity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201412231458206192340_2&ACE_SEARCH=1|title=Jung Yong-hwa releases his own song|date=23 November 2014|work=Kpop Herald}}</ref> \n\n[[File:Jung Yong-hwa - Shenzhen.jpg|left|thumb|Jung on the red carpet at the 15th Yinyue Fengyun Bang Awards on April 13, 2015]]\n\nIn January 2015, Jung debuted as a solo artist with the album ''[[One Fine Day (Jung Yong-hwa album)|One Fine Day]]'', which clinched the number one spot on the [[List of K-pop on the Billboard charts|''Billboard'' World Albums chart]].<ref>{{cite web|author=Jeff Benjamin |url=http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/k-town/6457931/cnblue-jung-yong-hwa-one-fine-day-no-1-world-albums |title=CNBLUE's Jung Yong Hwa Debuts at No. 1 on World Albums With 'One Fine Day' Solo Debut |work=Billboard |date=2015-01-29 |accessdate=2016-07-09}}</ref> The album featured artists [[JJ Lin]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2015/01/398_171624.html|title=CNBLUE's Jung Yong-hwa to collaborate with JJ Lin|website=The Korea Times|date=13 January 2015}}</ref> [[Yang Dong-geun]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201501071716259558313_2&ACE_SEARCH=1|title=Jung Yong-hwa sings duet with Yang Dong-geun|date=7 January 2015|work=Kpop Herald}}</ref> [[Verbal Jint]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mwave.me/en/news/news/view/84901/CN-Blue%E2%80%99s-Jung-Yong-Hwa-Unveils-VerbalJint-and-Yoon-Do-Hyun-as-Featured-Artists|title=CN Blue\u2019s Jung Yong Hwa Unveils VerbalJint and Yoon Do Hyun as Featured Artists|date=12 January 2015|work=enewsWorld}}</ref> [[YB (band)|YB]]'s [[Yoon Do-hyun]] and [[Peter Malick]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201501131549595313206_2&ACE_SEARCH=1|title=Jung Yong-hwa unveils lineup for collaboration|date=13 January 2015|work=Kpop Herald}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2999993|title=Jung calls new solo album \u2018perfect\u2019|website=Korea JoongAng Daily|date=23 January 2015}}</ref> ''One Fine Day'' received generally favorable reviews from music critics, who noted his growth as a singer-songwriter.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soompi.com/2015/01/12/jung-yong-hwas-musical-abilities-praised-by-ydg-verbal-jint-yoon-do-hyun/ |title=Jung Yong Hwa's Musical Abilities Praised By YDG, Verbal Jint, Yoon Do Hyun |work=Soompi |accessdate=2016-07-09}}</ref> Jung later embarked on his first series of solo concerts across Asia.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201501271804210557719_2&ACE_SEARCH=1|title=Jung Yong-hwa concert tickets sell out|date=27 January 2015|work=Kpop Herald}}</ref> \n\nIn 2016, Jung collaborated with [[Sunwoo Jung-a]] on a collaborative album project.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201601111811384633363_2&ACE_SEARCH=1|title=Jung Yong-hwa collaborates with Sunwoo Junga|date=11 January 2016|work=Kpop Herald}}</ref> The duo released two singles \u201cHello\u201d and \u201cEmpathy\u201d; Jung composed \"Hello\" and co-wrote the lyrics to \"Empathy\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201601141750326031578_2&ACE_SEARCH=1|title=Jung Yong-hwa and Sunwoo Jung-a\u2019s collaboration is \u2018destiny\u2019|date=14 January 2016|work=Kpop Herald}}</ref>  \n\nJung reportedly collaborated with foreign artists through a songwriting camp for his first EP,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2017/06/20/2017062001039.html|title=CNBLUE's Jung Yong-hwa to Release Solo Album Next Month|date=20 June 2017|work=The Chosun Ilbo}}</ref> titled ''[[Do Disturb]]''. The EP along with the music video for its lead single \"[[That Girl (Jung Yong-hwa song)|That Girl]]\" were released on July 19, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201707061855082772476_2&ACE_SEARCH=1|title=CNBLUE\u2019s Jung Yong-hwa to return with \u2018Do Disturb\u2019|date=6 July 2017|work=Kpop Herald}}</ref> Jung released his second Japanese album ''[[Summer Calling]]'' on August 9, 2017.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20170809000550|title=Jung Yong-hwa releases second solo album in Japan|date=9 August 2017|work=The Korea Herald}}</ref>\n\n===Songwriting===\nJung has composed several notable singles for CNBLUE, including \"[[In My Head (CNBLUE song)|In My Head]]\" (2011), \"[[Where You Are (CNBLUE song)|Where You Are]]\" (2012) and \"I'm Sorry\" (2013).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2013/02/04/2013020400381.html|title=CNBLUE Flashes Songwriting Skills in Eclectic New Album|date=4 February 2013|work=The Chosun Ilbo}}</ref> In particular, his composition \"[[Can't Stop (CNBLUE song)|Can't Stop]]\" for the group's [[Can't Stop (EP)|fifth EP]] was very well received and earned rave reviews from critics and K-pop fans.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20140312001508&ACE_SEARCH=1|title=Eyelike: CN Blue shows maturity on \u2018Can\u2019t Stop\u2019|date=14 March 2014|work=The Korea Herald}}</ref>    \n\nFor his drama ''[[Heartstrings (Korean TV series)|Heartstrings]]'' (2011), he composed and sang \"Because I Miss You\". The single peaked at number 14 on the [[Gaon Chart]], and later ranked number one on Japanese ringtone charts.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2963462|title=Jung Yong-hwa tops Japanese mobile phone ringtone chart|date=6 December 2012|work=Korea JoongAng Daily}}</ref> He also produced \"Casting Love\" for the soundtrack of ''[[Marry Him If You Dare]]'' (2013), which was sung by Jeon Gun-hwa. \n\nJung has also composed for other artists. He composed and produced \"Fool\" (also known as \"Babo\") as a gift for label-mate [[Juniel]], which was featured on her debut album<ref name=\"enews\">{{cite web|url=http://enewsworld.interest.me/enews/contents.asp?idx=6686 |title= Music CN Blue's Jung Yong Hwa Serves as Producer for Rookie Artist Juniel's Debut Album  |work=enewsWorld|date=15 May 2012|accessdate=2013-03-28}}</ref> as well as  \"Love is Only You\" for another FNC artist, girl group [[AOA (band)|AOA]].<ref name=\"AOA\">{{cite web|url=http://www.kpopstarz.com/articles/11596/20120728/jung-yong-hwa-song-for-girl-group-released.htm |title= CNBLUE Jung Yong Hwa's Song Produced for a Girl Group AOA is Released  |work= Kpopstarz|date=28 July 2012|accessdate=2013-03-28}}</ref> Jung released 17 compositions for the first half of 2012.<ref>{{cite web|script-title=ko:\uc528\uc5d4\ube14\ub8e8 \uc815\uc6a9\ud654, \uc62c \uc0c1\ubc18\uae30 \uc790\uc791\uace1\ub9cc 17\uace1 '\uc2e4\ub825 \uc778\uc99d'  |url=http://www.mydaily.co.kr/new_yk/html/read.php?newsid=201208051149461132 |language=korean| work=My Daily |accessdate=2013-03-31}}</ref>\n\nAs a gift for the ''CNBLUE School'' in Burkina Faso, Africa, Jung helped produce their \"School Song\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://entertainment.xin.msn.com/en/hallyu/cj/storyviewer.aspx?cp-documentid%3D252291367 |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2013-12-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131212101828/http://entertainment.xin.msn.com/en/hallyu/cj/storyviewer.aspx?cp-documentid=252291367 |archivedate=12 December 2013 }}</ref> In 2013, Jung penned the song \"Feel Good\", the brand song of [[Samsung Galaxy]], which was released on YouTube on August 23, 2013.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.soompi.com/2013/08/23/cnblue-pens-samsung-galaxys-brand-song-feel-good-releases-lighthearted-mv-2/ |title=CNBlue Pens Samsung Galaxy's Brand Song \"Feel Good,\" Releases Lighthearted MV |work=Soompi |accessdate=2016-07-09}}</ref>\n\nIn January 2019, Jung was among 25 songwriters selected for the forthcoming year to become full members of the [[Korea Music Copyright Association]] (KOMCA).<ref>https://www.hellokpop.com/news/full-members-komca-2019/</ref>\n\n==Acting career==\n[[File:Jung Yong-hwa - Happy Camp filming.jpg|thumbnail|Jung filming ''[[Happy Camp (variety show)|Happy Camp]]'' in China, 2015]]\nJung Yong-hwa debuted as an actor before his band's debut in Korea. He was the first member of CNBLUE to appear on screen in 2009 when he landed his first acting role in the [[Seoul Broadcasting System|SBS]] drama ''[[You're Beautiful (TV series)|You're Beautiful]].'' The drama aired from October 7 to November 26, 2009.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.tenasia.com/archives/1063|title=My Name\u2026 Jung Yong-hwa|date=1 December 2009|work=10Asia}}</ref> As the series revolves around the life of a musical group, he played the role of the lead guitarist in the faux idol band A.N.Jell.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sportsworldi.segye.com/content/html/2009/09/23/20090923001422.html|title=\u2018\ubbf8\ub0a8\uc774\uc2dc\ub124\uc694\u2019 A.N.JELL \ud3ec\uc2a4\ud130 \uacf5\uac1c - \uc2a4\ud3ec\uce20\uc6d4\ub4dc|work=Sports World|language=ko|access-date=2016-10-30}}</ref> The series gained a cult following,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://isplus.live.joins.com/news/article/article.asp?total_id=3851058 |title=\u2018\ubbf8\ub0a8\uc774\uc2dc\ub124\uc694\u2019\uac00 \u2018\uc544\uc774\ub9ac\uc2a4\u2019\uc5d0 \uae30\uc8fd\uc9c0 \uc54a\ub294 \uc774\uc720 - \uc77c\uac04\uc2a4\ud3ec\uce20 |website=[[JoongAng Ilbo]]|date=30 October 2009 |accessdate=|language=Korean}}</ref> and earned high ratings in Japan,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.asiae.co.kr/news/view.htm?idxno=2010080508424241476|title=Korean drama \"Minamishineyo\" scores top rating in Japan|website=10Asia|date=5 August 2010}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hancinema.net/jang-geun-seok-you-re-beautiful-beats-winter-sonata-33223.html |title=Jang Geun-seok \"You're Beautiful\" beats \"Winter Sonata\"|website=[[HanCinema]]|date=14 September 2011 |accessdate=}}</ref> which fostered the growth of his popularity.<ref name=\"Joy\">{{cite web|last1=Lee|first1=Mi-yeong|script-title=ko:\uc815\uc6a9\ud654, \ud574\uc678 \ub7ec\ube0c\ucf5c \ubd07\ubb3c\u2026\"\ub0b4\ub144 \ud55c\uad6d \ub370\ubdd4\uac00 \uba3c\uc800\"|url=http://joynews.inews24.com/php/news_view.php?g_menu=700100&g_serial=460691|website=Joynews24|publisher=inews24|accessdate=|language=Korean|date=1 December 2009}}</ref>\n\nIn 2011, Jung was cast in MBC's youth campus drama ''[[Heartstrings (Korean TV series)|Heartstrings]]'', along with fellow band member [[Kang Min-hyuk]]. The drama also reunited Jung with ''You're Beautiful'' co-star [[Park Shin-hye]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Kwon|first=Mee-yoo|title=Campus romance to pull at Heartstrings|url=http://www.koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/art/2011/06/201_89788.html|work=[[The Korea Times]]|accessdate=2014-02-21|date=28 June 2011}}</ref> After the drama aired, Jung experienced a rise in popularity in Japan.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2952874|title=Japan has fallen for Jung Yong-hwa|date=17 May 2012|work=Korea JoongAng Daily}}</ref> \n\nOriginally cast in [[Kim Eun-sook]]'s teen drama ''[[The Heirs]]'', Jung revealed that he declined the role to \"avoid\" actress [[Park Shin-hye]] (who was the lead actress of ''Heirs'') despite being fascinated with the character and knowing that the drama was likely to succeed.<ref name=heirs>{{cite web|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2985949|title=CN Blue singer avoiding friend|date=7 March 2014|work=Korea JoongAng Daily}}</ref> Instead, he chose to star in KBS' romantic comedy ''[[Marry Him If You Dare]]''.<ref>{{cite web|last=Jeon|first=Su-mi|title=CN Blue\u2032s Jung Yong Hwa, Yun Eun Hye and Lee Dong Gun Confirmed for Drama ''The Choice of the Future''|url=http://mwave.interest.me/enewsworld/en/article/44413|work=enewsWorld|accessdate=2013-09-05|date=27 August 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130830003331/http://mwave.interest.me/enewsworld/en/article/44413|archive-date=August 30, 2013|url-status=dead}}</ref> Explaining his decision, Jung said that the audience is likely to be \"bored\" as he had already worked with Park in two dramas.<ref name=heirs />  \n\nIn 2014, Jung took the leading role in period action drama ''[[The Three Musketeers (2014 TV series)|The Three Musketeers]]''.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://osen.mt.co.kr/article/G1109869905|title=\uc774\uc9c4\uc6b1-\uc591\ub3d9\uadfc-\uc815\uc6a9\ud654, '\uc0bc\ucd1d\uc0ac' \uc724\uacfd \ub4dc\ub7ec\ub0ac\ub2e4|access-date=2016-10-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Kim|first1=Min-jin|title=Jung Yong-hwa proves quality as actor in ''Three Musketeers''|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20140902001005|website=[[The Korea Herald]]|accessdate=2014-09-03|date=2 September 2014}}</ref> Despite suffering from low ratings,<ref>{{cite web|last1=Park|first1=Gyu-oh|title=''Three Musketeers'' 2nd season postponed|url=http://www.kpopherald.com/view.php?ud=201412091939247293841_2|website=[[The Korea Herald|K-Pop Herald]]|accessdate=2014-12-16|date=9 December 2014}}</ref> Jung received positive reviews from critics and producers for his improved acting in the series.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201410261818340932048_2&ACE_SEARCH=1|title=Jung Yong-hwa applauded for his wonderful acting|date=26 October 2014|work=Kpop Herald}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201411031706365245341_2&ACE_SEARCH=1|title=Jung Yong-hwa highly praised by drama producers|date=3 November 2014|work=Kpop Herald}}</ref> ''Three Musketeers'' was also well-received in China and fostered in Jung's growth in popularity in the country.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=20140828000921&ACE_SEARCH=1|title=Jung Yong-hwa seizes China\u2019s heart with \u2018Three Musketeers\u2019|date=28 August 2014|work=The Korea Herald}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201411181324392041130_2&ACE_SEARCH=1|title=Jung Yong-hwa basks in explosive popularity in China|date=18 November 2014|work=Kpop Herald}}</ref>\n\nIn 2017, Jung made his big-screen debut in the Chinese gastronomy film ''[[Cook Up a Storm]]'' alongside [[Nicholas Tse]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201612141724080084322_2|title=Jung Yong-hwa to make Chinese movie debut in January|website=Kpop Herald|access-date=2016-12-27}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.scmp.com/culture/film-tv/article/2069880/film-review-cook-storm-nicholas-tse-jung-yong-hwa-face-culinary|title=Cook Up a Storm \u2013 Nicholas Tse, Jung Yong-hwa face off in culinary comedy|date=10 February 2017|work=South China Morning Post}}</ref> The same year, Jung starred in [[JTBC]]'s travel romance drama ''[[The Package (TV series)|The Package]]'' with [[Lee Yeon-hee]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=3022149|title=Jung Yong-hwa and Lee Yeon-hee sign on for JTBC's 'The Package'|date=3 August 2016|work=Korea JoongAng Daily}}</ref> \n\n===Variety show===\nAfter his successful acting debut, Jung joined his first variety show, [[Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation|MBC]]'s ''[[Sunday Sunday Night]]'' program ''Korea Ecosystem Rescue Centre: Hunters'', which featured seven celebrity MCs going out to capture wild boars. The show premiered on December 6, 2009 but was forced to prematurely cease its run in mid-January 2010 due to protests by animal-rights groups.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://animalrightskorea.org/actions/irresponsible-mbc-to-televise-hunting-program.html |title=Irresponsible MBC to Televise Hunting Program |publisher=Korea Animal Rights Advocates |date=27 November 2009 |accessdate=2011-03-28 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111013161457/http://animalrightskorea.org/actions/irresponsible-mbc-to-televise-hunting-program.html |archive-date=October 13, 2011 |url-status=dead }}</ref> He subsequently continued as one of the MCs on the replacement program ''Eco House'', which deals with global climate change.\n\nIn 2010, Jung became the one of the hosts of [[Seoul Broadcasting System|SBS]]' live music show ''[[Inkigayo]]'' and variety-talk show ''Night After Night''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.tenasia.com/archives/3584|title=Jo Kwon, Jung Yong-hwa to host SBS music show|date=13 July 2010|work=10Asia}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.mk.co.kr/newsRead.php?year=2010&no=555407|title=\uc815\uc6a9\ud654-\uc720\uc774-\ub300\uc131 `\ubc24\uc774\uba74 \ubc24\ub9c8\ub2e4` MC \ub099\uc810|website=MK News|language=ko}}</ref>  He left both programs in 2011.\n\nIn February 2010, he was paired with [[Seohyun]] of [[Girls' Generation]] as part of a virtually wedded couple for MBC's ''[[We Got Married]]''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://star.mt.co.kr/view/stview.php?no=2010021610280721842&outlink=2&SVEC|title=\uc815\uc6a9\ud654-\uc11c\ud604, '\uc6b0\uacb0' \uc0c8\ucee4\ud50c - \uc2a4\ud0c0\ub274\uc2a4|website=Star News|language=ko|access-date=2016-10-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.tenasia.com/archives/1851|title=Idols Jung Yong-hwa, Seohyun join cast of MBC reality show|date=26 February 2010|work=10Asia}}</ref> Collectively known as \"YongSeo\" couple, they filmed their final episode of the show on March 15, 2011.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://en.tenasia.com/archives/6460|title=Jung Yong-hwa-Seohyun couple bids goodbye to make-believe marriage show|date=27 March 2011|work=10Asia}}</ref> At the end of the year, Jung won the \"Popularity Award\" at the [[MBC Entertainment Awards]] for his stint in ''We Got Married''.\n\nIn 2018, Jung joined the talk show ''Talk Mon'' alongside [[Kang Ho-dong]] as a host. However, he shortly left the program soon after he was involved in a controversy.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201712101720196855064_2&ACE_SEARCH=1|title=CNBLUE\u2019s Jung Yong-hwa to become main MC for upcoming talk show|date=13 December 2017|work=Kpop Herald}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.yonhapnews.co.kr/kwave/2018/01/17/3001000000AEN20180117014600315.html|title=CNBLUE's Jung Yong-hwa quits TV show amid controversy over academic favor|date=17 January 2018|work=Yonhap News Agency}}</ref>\n\n== Personal life ==\n===Philanthropy===\nJung has actively participated in charity events in the previous years including in the event held by BC Card in Seoul last May 2015.<ref>https://www.kpopstarz.com/articles/201744/20150515/cnblue-jung-yong-hwa-charity.htm</ref>\n\nHe has released a song called [[You, My Star]] on December 23, 2013, dedicated to his fans. All the proceeds from this song have been donated to the FNC charity, Love FNC.\n\nOn December 2017, it has been reported that Jung has taken part in a public campaign for children with hearing disabilities run by Audiology Development Foundation in China. This campaign will help pay for the costs of education and other needs of children with hearing disabilities.<ref>http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201712281452587222739_2</ref>\n\nJung held a two-day concert in March 2018 before he enlisted. All the profits in the said event will be donated.<ref>http://kpoplove.koreadaily.com/cnblue-jung-yong-hwa-hold-one-last-fan-meet-entering-military/</ref>\n\nHe donated 50 million won to the Miral Welfare Foundation to celebrate this year's International Day of Disabled Persons on December 3. He requested that the donation will be used for the medical and living expenses of disabled children from low-income families.\u00a0<ref>http://pop.heraldcorp.com/view.php?ud=201812060752227076264_1</ref>\n\nHe established a scholarship program at his alma mater, Namsan High School in Busan. He attended the graduation ceremony held on February 12, 2019, awarding six scholarships to selected graduates. He also donated to the school\u2019s development and will continuously do so.<ref>http://kpoplove.koreadaily.com/cnblue-jung-yong-hwa-establishes-scholarship-program-at-busan-school/</ref>\n\nJung donated 20 million won for the victims of forest fires Gangwon Province through\u00a0Hope Bridge National Disaster Relief Association. According to the organization, the donation will be used for the recovery of the damaged areas in Gangwon Province and support for the victims.<ref>https://m.entertain.naver.com/read?oid=311&aid=0000976021</ref>\n\n=== Controversy ===\nOn June 28, 2016 it was reported that Jung is being under investigation for [[insider trading]]. He was reportedly being investigated for allegedly earning approximately $347,000 through buying stocks in [[FNC Entertainment]] after learning about their plans to sign a major celebrity.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://koreatimes.co.kr/www/news/nation/2016/06/398_208165.html|title=K-pop band CNBLUE leader quizzed over alleged insider trading|date=29 June 2016|work=The Korea Times}}</ref> On June 30, Jung was cleared of suspicion and was found not guilty.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201607011506415684771_2&ACE_SEARCH=1|title=CNBLUE\u2019s Jung Yong-hwa acquitted of insider trading charges|date=1 July 2016|work=Kpop Herald}}</ref> On October 31, FNC Entertainment announced that they would take legal action against malicious rumors about the singer after being framed of insider trading.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joins.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=3025647|title=CNBlue\u2019s agency take action against rumors|date=2 November 2016|work=Korea JoongAng Daily}}</ref>\n\nOn January 17, 2018, Jung was reported to have entered a [[Kyung Hee University]] graduate school program, despite failing to appear at two official interviews for graduate school entrance.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201801171500091091186_2|title=Jung Yong-hwa apologizes for \u2018expedient entry\u2019 to grad school|date=17 January 2018|work=Kpop Herald}}</ref> It was later revealed that he attended the interview separately at his agency FNC Entertainment at the request of the professor in charge of student admission.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://hei.hankyung.com/news/app/newsview.php?aid=201801178338H|title=\uc815\uc6a9\ud654 \uc18c\uc18d\uc0ac \uce21 \"\ud3b8\ubc95 \uc785\ud559 \uc758\ub3c4\u7121\u2026\ubb3c\uc758 \ube5a\uc5b4 \uc8c4\uc1a1\" (\uc804\ubb38)|date=2018-01-17|work=\uc815\uc6a9\ud654 \uc18c\uc18d\uc0ac \uce21 \"\ud3b8\ubc95 \uc785\ud559 \uc758\ub3c4\u7121\u2026\ubb3c\uc758 \ube5a\uc5b4 \uc8c4\uc1a1\" (\uc804\ubb38)|access-date=2018-02-26|language=ko-KR}}</ref> Due to the controversy, Jung's admission was set to be revoked by Kyung Hee University despite having not broken any rules as the university itself has no clear rules regarding graduate student admission process, and that it's often up to the professor's discretion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201801192127202489835_2|title=University set to revoke Jung Yong-hwa's admission over unfair treatment|date=19 January 2018|work=Kpop Herald}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dispatch.co.kr/1096188|title=[Q&D] \u201c\uad00\ub840\uc778\uac00, \ud2b9\ud61c\uc778\uac00\u201d\u2026\uc815\uc6a9\ud654, \ud3b8\ubc95 \ub17c\ub780\uc758 \ucd9c\ubc1c|date=2018-01-17|work=\ub514\uc2a4\ud328\uce58 {{!}} \ub274\uc2a4\ub294 \ud329\ud2b8\ub2e4!|access-date=2018-02-26|language=ko-KR}}</ref> Citizens\u2019 Coalition for Democratic Media (CCDM) issued a press release criticizing SBS for targeting Jung in their report, calling it \"exploitative\" and \"extremely inappropriate reporting by the media that runs the serious risk of human rights violations.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ccdm.or.kr/xe/index.php?mid=watch&category=6292&document_srl=244326|title=SBS \uacbd\ud76c\ub300 \uc785\ud559\ud2b9\ud61c \ubcf4\ub3c4, \u2018\uc544\uc774\ub3cc\u2019\ub9cc \ub0a8\uc558\ub2e4 - \ubbfc\uc5b8\ub828 \uc5b8\ub860\ubaa8\ub2c8\ud130 - \ubbfc\uc8fc\uc5b8\ub860\uc2dc\ubbfc\uc5f0\ud569|date=2018-01-18|work=\ubbfc\uc8fc\uc5b8\ub860\uc2dc\ubbfc\uc5f0\ud569|access-date=2018-02-26|language=ko-KR}}</ref> \n\nOn October 9, 2018, FNC Entertainment announced that Jung had been cleared of all charges earlier that year. It was reported that Jung was not guilty of obstruction of business in regards to his school admissions. The prosecutor decided to not indict him in July. The law also acknowledged that Jung did not have any intention of receiving preferential admission.<ref>https://www.soompi.com/article/1242727wpp/cnblues-jung-yong-hwa-cleared-charges-preferential-admission-case</ref>\n\n===Mandatory military service===\nJung began his compulsory military service on March 5, 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://kpopherald.koreaherald.com/view.php?ud=201801261029508678665_2|title=Jung Yong-hwa to enlist on March 5|date=26 January 2018|work=Kpop Herald}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://english.chosun.com/site/data/html_dir/2018/03/06/2018030600968.html|title=CNBLUE's Jung Yong-hwa Joins Military Amid Allegations of Academic Favoritism|date=6 March 2018|website=The Chosun Ilbo}}</ref>\n\nJung volunteered to be assigned in the 702nd Special Assault Regiment in Second Corps on April 13, 2018.<ref>https://www.soompi.com/article/1154787wpp/cnblues-jung-yong-hwa-assigned-special-forces-volunteering</ref>\n\nJung was discharged from his military service on November 3, 2019.<ref>http://news.kstyle.com/article.ksn?articleNo=2129387</ref><ref>https://www.soompi.com/article/1363350wpp/cnblues-jung-yong-hwa-discharged-from-military-promises-to-show-a-more-mature-side-of-himself-in-future</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n=== Film ===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n!Year\n!Title\n!Role\n!Notes\n|-\n|2017\n|''[[Cook Up a Storm]]''\n|Chef Ahn Paul\n|\n|}\n\n===Television series===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year !! Network !! Title !! Role !! Notes\n|-\n| 2009 || [[Seoul Broadcasting System|SBS]] || ''[[You're Beautiful (TV series)|You're Beautiful]]'' || Kang Shin-woo || Second lead\n|-\n| 2011 || [[Munhwa Broadcasting Corporation|MBC]] || ''[[Heartstrings (Korean TV series)|Heartstrings]]'' || Lee Shin|| Main lead\n|-\n| 2012 || [[Seoul Broadcasting System|SBS]] || ''[[A Gentleman's Dignity]]'' || Himself || Cameo (Episode 13)<ref>{{cite news|last=Sunwoo|first=Carla|title=Jung Yong-hwa to make cameo appearance in ''A Gentleman's Dignity''|url=http://koreajoongangdaily.joinsmsn.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2955581|accessdate=2012-07-04|newspaper=Korea Joongang Daily|date=5 July 2012|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20121003013243/http://koreajoongangdaily.joinsmsn.com/news/article/article.aspx?aid=2955581|archivedate=October 3, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref> \n|-\n|2013 || [[KBS2]] || ''[[Marry Him If You Dare]]'' || Park Se-joo || Second lead \n|-\n| 2014 || [[TVN (South Korea)|tvN]] || ''[[The Three Musketeers (2014 TV series)|The Three Musketeers]]'' || Park Dal-hyang || Main lead\n|-\n| 2017 || [[jTBC]] ||[[The Package (TV series)|''The Package'']]|| San Ma-roo || Main lead\n|}\n\n===Variety and reality show===\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" 